      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/ncv",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Code verification acceptance criteria — MRL 2",
        "description": "Solver passes manufacturer-supplied benchmark suite for incompressible Navier-Stokes and scalar transport. Order-of-accuracy verified on manufactured solution for hemolysis scalar transport equation."
      },
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent benchmark suite results documented in solver release notes. Independent order-of-accuracy study on a 2D pipe-flow manufactured solution confirmed second-order spatial convergence for the hemolysis scalar, consistent with MRL 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/de",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/de",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Discretization error acceptance criteria — MRL 2",
        "description": "Grid convergence index (GCI) < 5% for primary QoI (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH) on fine-to-medium mesh pair. Three mesh levels (coarse ~1.2M, medium ~4.8M, fine ~19M cells) assessed per Celik et al. 2008 procedure."
      },
      "rationale": "GCI study conducted at all five operating points. Fine-mesh GCI for NIH ranged 0.8–2.1%, well below the 5% threshold. Apparent order of convergence was 1.92, consistent with second-order discretization. Achieved level 3 due to systematic three-level Richardson extrapolation with reported extrapolated values."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/tc",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/tc",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions acceptance criteria — MRL 2",
        "description": "Experimental test conditions (flow rates, rotational speeds, fluid properties) are documented and match CFD boundary conditions within stated measurement uncertainties. Blood analog fluid properties (viscosity, density) reported with traceability."
      },
      "rationale": "FDA GCBP experimental dataset provides documented flow rates (2–8 L/min), rotational speeds (2000–3500 RPM), and fluid properties for porcine blood. CFD boundary conditions set to match reported mean values. Measurement uncertainties for flow (±0.5%) and speed (±10 RPM) propagated into simulation input uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/oc",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/oc",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison acceptance criteria — MRL 2",
        "description": "CFD-predicted NIH values compared against experimental NIH measurements at five operating points. Agreement metric: relative error < 20% at each point, consistent with MRL 2 validation requirements for hemolysis prediction."
      },
      "rationale": "CFD NIH predictions at all five operating points fell within 12% of experimental mean values. The worst-case point (5 L/min, 3500 RPM) showed 11.8% relative error, within the 20% acceptance threshold. Systematic bias of +4.2% attributed to power-law model form and documented as acceptable at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/rqoi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/rqoi",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance acceptance criteria — MRL 2",
        "description": "Primary QoI (NIH and relative hemolysis index RHI) are directly linked to the clinical decision endpoint (hemolysis risk). Secondary QoI (pressure rise, torque) serve as surrogate indicators and are also compared."
      },
      "rationale": "NIH and RHI are the regulatory-standard hemolysis metrics cited in FDA guidance for CPB devices. The decision endpoint — whether RHI < 1.0 relative to predicate — maps directly to the primary QoI. Secondary QoI (pressure-flow curve) provide additional model fidelity evidence without displacing the primary metric."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/rvac",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/rvac",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation relevance acceptance criteria — MRL 2",
        "description": "Validation activities performed on the same FDA GCBP geometry and fluid system as the COU. Operating conditions span the intended COU envelope. Validation dataset is independent of model calibration data."
      },
      "rationale": "Validation experiments used the FDA GCBP physical model — the same geometry as the simulation target. Five operating points bracket the COU envelope (2–8 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM). The experimental dataset was not used to calibrate any model parameter, preserving independence."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/nse",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error is addressed within the Discretization error and Numerical code verification factors for MRL 2. Separate explicit assessment of iterative convergence error is scoped out because residual convergence to 1e-6 (mass, momentum, scalar) was documented at all operating points, and the GCI study bounds the combined numerical error. No additional standalone assessment is required at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/ue",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment is scoped out at MRL 2 for this COU. The simulation workflow is executed by a single experienced analyst team using a controlled, version-locked simulation template. Peer review of boundary condition setup and post-processing scripts was conducted and documented. A formal human-factors use-error analysis is not required at MRL 2 per ASME V&V 40 Table 3."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/mf",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty assessment beyond what is captured in the Output comparison factor is scoped out at MRL 2. The k-omega SST turbulence model and Giersiepen power-law hemolysis model are standard choices for CPB CFD with documented literature benchmarks. A formal model-form uncertainty quantification study (e.g., multi-model ensemble) is not required at MRL 2 per ASME V&V 40 credibility factor requirements."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/mi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Detailed model input uncertainty propagation beyond boundary condition matching is scoped out at MRL 2. Fluid properties (viscosity, density) are held at nominal values with measurement uncertainty documented. A full probabilistic sensitivity study of all input parameters is not required at MRL 2; the Test conditions factor captures the relevant boundary condition uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/ts",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Test sample variability assessment is scoped out at MRL 2. The FDA GCBP is a standardized reference geometry manufactured to tight tolerances; unit-to-unit geometric variability is negligible for the purposes of this credibility assessment. Sample-to-sample biological variability in porcine blood is partially addressed through the experimental uncertainty reported in the FDA dataset."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/eip",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "scoped-out",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters is scoped out at MRL 2 because the validation study uses the same geometry, fluid, and operating conditions as the COU. There is no extrapolation from a surrogate test article or surrogate fluid system; therefore a formal equivalency argument is not required. The Relevance of validation activities factor documents the direct correspondence between validation and COU conditions."
